/-!

# Equivalent Lagrangians under Total Derivatives

## i. Overview

Two Lagrangians are physically equivalent if they differ by a total time derivative
d/dt F(q, t). This is because the Euler-Lagrange equations depend only on extremizing
the action integral, and total derivatives don't affect which paths are extremal.

This module defines the key concept of a function being a total time derivative,
which is essential for analyzing symmetries like Galilean invariance.

Note: Some authors call this "gauge equivalence" by analogy with gauge transformations
in field theory, but we avoid that terminology here since no gauge fields are involved.

## ii. Key insight

A general function خ´L(r, v, t) is a total time derivative if there exists a function
F(r, t) (independent of velocity) such that:
  خ´L(r, v, t) = d/dt F(r, t) = fderiv â„‌ F (r, t) (v, 1)

By the chain rule, this expands to:
  خ´L(r, v, t) = âˆ‚F/âˆ‚t + âں¨âˆ‡لµ£F, vâں©

For the special case where خ´L depends only on velocity v (not position or time),
this implies a strong constraint:
  خ´L(v) = âں¨g, vâں© for some constant vector g

This is because:
1. d/dt F(r, t) = âˆ‚F/âˆ‚t + âں¨âˆ‡F, vâں©
2. For خ´L to be r-independent, âˆ‡F must be r-independent
3. For خ´L to be t-independent, the time-dependent part must vanish
4. The result is خ´L = âں¨g, vâں© for constant g

## iii. Key definitions

- `IsTotalTimeDerivative`: General case for خ´L(r, v, t)
- `IsTotalTimeDerivativeVelocity`: Velocity-only case, equivalent to خ´L(v) = âں¨g, vâں©

## iv. References

- Landau & Lifshitz, "Mechanics", آ§2 (The principle of least action)
- Landau & Lifshitz, "Mechanics", آ§4 (The Lagrangian for a free particle)

-/

namespace ClassicalMechanics

open InnerProductSpace

namespace Lagrangian

/-!

## A. General Total Time Derivative

-/

/-- A function خ´L(r, v, t) is a total time derivative if it can be written as d/dt F(r, t)
    for some function F that depends on position and time but not velocity.

    Mathematically: خ´L(r, v, t) = fderiv â„‌ F (r, t) (v, 1)

    By the chain rule, this equals âˆ‚F/âˆ‚t + âں¨âˆ‡لµ£F, vâں©.

    This is the most general form of Lagrangian equivalence under total derivatives.
    The key point is that F must be independent of velocity. -/
def IsTotalTimeDerivative {n : â„•}
    (خ´L : EuclideanSpace â„‌ (Fin n) â†’ EuclideanSpace â„‌ (Fin n) â†’ â„‌ â†’ â„‌) : Prop :=
  âˆƒ (F : EuclideanSpace â„‌ (Fin n) أ— â„‌ â†’ â„‌) (_ : Differentiable â„‌ F),
    âˆ€ r v t, خ´L r v t = fderiv â„‌ F (r, t) (v, 1)

/-!

## B. Velocity-Only Total Time Derivative

When خ´L depends only on velocity (the free particle case), the condition simplifies.

-/

/-- A velocity-only function that is a total time derivative must be linear in velocity.

    If خ´L depends only on velocity and equals d/dt F(r, t) for some F,
    then خ´L(v) = âں¨g, vâں© for some constant vector g.

